The '''1983 Upper Voltan coup d'état attempt''' was an event which took place on 28 February 1983, in the [[Republic of Upper Volta]] (today [[Burkina Faso]]), just a few months after a previous ''[[1982 Upper Voltan coup d'état|coup d'état]]'' on 7 November 1982, carried out by radical elements of the [[Military of Burkina Faso|army]] against the regime of Colonel [[Saye Zerbo]], who himself came to power in a [[1980 Upper Voltan coup d'état|1980 coup]] against Major General [[Sangoulé Lamizana]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Manson |first1=Katrina |last2=Knight |first2=James |date=2012 |title=Burkina Faso |location=[[Chalfont St Peter]] |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |pages=26–27 |isbn=184-162-352-0}}</ref> The coup attempt on 28 February, which targeted the Council of Popular Salvation and its leader Major [[Jean-Baptiste Ouédraogo]], failed.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rupley |first1=Lawrence |last2=Bangali |first2=Lamissa |last3=Diamitani |first3=Boureima |date=2013 |title=Historical Dictionary of Burkina Faso|location=[[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham]] |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield|Scarecrow Press]] |page=52 |isbn=081-088-010-5}}</ref>

Several army officers intended to massacre the CSP in assembly and restore Zerbo's regime. When they delayed they were arrested by other officials. One of the leading putschists was a commandant who had been considered for the presidency following the 1982 coup. When questioned about the incident, Ouédraogo told the press, "Since our regime makes many people uneasy, it is quite normal that people should plan this sort of reaction."{{sfn|Recent Unsuccessful Coup Attempt Explained|1983|p=770}} He publicly declared his determination to "guarantee order and security" and asserted that "the army will not allow itself to be dissuaded by tribal fights and ideologies". He also stated that corruption and fraud in the business community had, in part, facilitated the state of "total anarchy" over which the government presided, and announced that the national administration would be restructured to mitigate the disorder.{{sfn|Coup Plot Discovered|1983|p=6781}}

President Ouédraogo would however not remain in power for long – large protest against his rule began on 17 May, after he purged the government of several radicals including Captain [[Thomas Sankara]]. Within a few months, he was deposed in a coup on 3 August, led by Captain [[Blaise Compaoré]], who made his close friend Sankara President. This began a period of societal transformation in Upper Volta, soon renamed Burkina Faso by the left-wing revolutionary Sankara, who himself would be overthrown in 1987 by Compaoré.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Heads of States and Governments Since 1945 |editor-last=Lentz |editor-first=Harris M. |location=[[London]] |publisher=[[Routledge]] |page=122 |date=2014 |isbn=113-426-490-9}}</ref>

