{{Infobox language |name=Lega |nativename= |states=[[DR Congo]] |region= |ethnicity=[[Lega people|Lega]] |speakers={{sigfig|449,000|2}} |date=1982–2000 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Bantoid languages|Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] ([[Guthrie classification of Bantu languages#Zone D|Zone D.20]]) |fam6=[[Lega–Binja languages|Lega–Binja]] |fam7=Lega–Bemba |lc1=lea|ld1=Shabunda Lega |lc2=lgm|ld2=Mwenga Lega |lc3=khx|ld3=Kanu |lc4=ktf|ld4=Kwami |glotto=lega1253 |glottorefname=Lega |guthrie=D.25,251 }} '''Lega''' is a [[Bantu language]], or [[dialect cluster]], of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]. There are two major varieties, '''Shabunda Lega''' and '''Mwenga Lega'''; Mwenga Lega, with about 10% of speakers, finds Shabunda difficult to understand. ''Kanu'' has been assigned a separate ISO code but is a dialect of Shabunda, and no more divergent than other dialects.
Variant spellings of 'Lega' are ''Rega, Leka, Ileka, Kilega, Kirega.'' Shabunda is also known as ''Igonzabale'', and Mwenga as ''Shile'' or ''Ishile''. [[Gengele language|Gengele]] is reported to be a Shabunda-based [[creole language|creole]].
According to ''Ethnologue'', '''[[Bembe language (Ibembe)|Bembe]]''' is part of the same dialect continuum. [[Nyindu language|Nyindu]] is a dialect of Shi that has been heavily influenced by Lega.
