{{Infobox ethnic group
|group    = '''Moni people'''<br />'''<small>Migani / Megani / Djonggunu / Jonggunu</small>'''
|image    = 
|caption  = 
|population  = 28,200<ref>{{cite web|url=http://joshuaproject.net/people_groups/13790/ID |title=Moni in Indonesia |publisher=[[Joshua Project]] |accessdate=2014-09-18}}</ref>
|popplace = {{flag|Indonesia}} ([[Papua (province)]])
|langs    = [[Moni language]], [[Indonesian language]]
|rels     = [[Christianity]] (predominantly), [[Animism]]
|related  = [[Papuan people|Papuan]]
}}

The '''Moni''' (also known as the '''Migani''', the '''Megani''', the '''Djonggunu''', or the '''Jonggunu''')  are an indigenous people in the Indonesian [[Paniai Regency|Paniai regency]] (kabupaten) of the [[Papua (province)|Papua province]] (formerly Central Irian Jaya) of [[West Papua (region)|West Papua]] (western part of the island of [[New Guinea]]). They speak the [[Moni language]]. They revere a large black and white whistling [[tree kangaroo]] called a [[Dingiso|bondegzeu]] as an ancestor. The bondegzeu was unknown to the [[scientific community]] until the [[zoologist]] [[Tim Flannery]] described it in 1995.<ref>{{cite book | title=The book of lists: the original compendium of curious information|author1=David Wallechinsky |author2=Amy Wallace |author3=Ira Basen |author4=Jane Farrow | publisher=Alfred A. Knopf Canada| year=2005 |pages=154|isbn=0-676-97720-0}}</ref>

