{{Royal house | surname = Sultanate of Dawaro | estate = [[Horn of Africa]] | coat of arms = | parent house = | country = {{flag|Ethiopia}} | titles = [[Sultan|Sulṭān]] | founder = ʿAli Madaḥweyne Dir Aji Irir Samāle | final ruler = }} The '''Sultanate of Dawaro''' was a [[Somalis|Somali]] [[Muslim]] [[Sultanate]] founded around the 10th century by the Jarso people sub-clan of the [[Dir (clan)|Dir]] clan centred in Hararghe.<ref name="Dawaro Sultanate">https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HGnyk8Pg9NgC&pg=PA12&dq=southern+ethiopian+muslim+sultanates&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtwKOP9vPZAhXCAsAKHfCdCu4Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=southern%20ethiopian%20muslim%20sultanates&f=false</ref>
==Origins== By Somali reckoning, the founder of Dawaro Sultanate was Jārso people belonging to the Ali Madaḥweyne branch which is a sub-clan of [[Dir (clan)|Dir]]. After the [[Oromo migrations]], the ʿAli Madaḥweyne Dir were absorbed into the Afran Qallo Barentuma confederation, and today the Jarso are reckoned as Jārsō Daggā Qāllō Barentuma Oromō.<ref name="Assimilation">https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fg1zCgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Oromo+assimilated+dir&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwicnLTF9fPZAhWFXMAKHUz6ArcQ6AEIOTAD#v=onepage&q&f=false</ref>
==Vassal state== Emperor [[Amda Seyon I]] of [[Ethiopian Empire|Abyssinia]] conquered many of the adjacent independent Muslim sultanates during his reign. In 1329, Sulṭān Ḥaydar of Dawaro was captured and imprisoned together with his ally Sulṭān [[Sabr ad-Din I|Sabir ad-Dīn Maḥamed]]. Despite several rebellions and a brief period when [[Badlay ibn Sa'ad ad-Din|Ahmeduddin Badlay]] a powerful [[Somalis|Somali]] ruler from [[Adal Sultanate]] captured Dawaro and turned it into a vessel of Adal and after the weakening of [[Adal Sultanate]], the opportunist [[Oromos]] captured the vessel state and assimilated the local native Somali population. Just like many [[Somalis]] in Hararghe, the Jarso people were also assimilated into the Oromo confederation after the weakening of Adal Sultanate by its war with the [[Ethiopian Empire]] and [[Portuguese Empire]].<ref>Futūḥ al-Ḥabasha. (n.d.). Christian-Muslim Relations 1500 - 1900. doi:10.1163/2451-9537_cmrii_com_26077</ref>
==Legacy== Dawaro was a major power prior to its defeat and subjugation. It was roughly equal in size, population and power to the early [[Ifat Sultanate]].<ref>Islamic History and Culture in Southern Ethiopia: Collected Essays</ref>
==Sultans of Dawaro== {| class="wikitable" |- ! !! Ruler Name !! Reign !! Note |- | ? | style=white-space:nowrap| Ḥaydar (or Haydara) | style=white-space:nowrap| ??? - 1329 | Ally of Sulṭān [[Sabr ad-Din I|'''SabiradDīn Maḥamed''' "Waqōyi" Naḥwi]] of [[Ifat Sultanate|Ifat]], imprisoned along with him by [[Amda Seyon I]] |}
